            <q>he has the assistance of counsel or a solicitor".</q>
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_370gc' title='Col. 370GC &mdash; HL Deb 19 June 2003 vol 649 c370GC' name='column_370gc' href='#column_370gc' rel='bookmark'>370GC</a>
            The Law Society of Scotland points out that in Scotland there is an alternative. A solicitor could instruct a solicitor-advocate to represent his client&#x2014;that is, a solicitor who has been granted rights of audience in various courts, including the High Court of Justiciary. To ensure that this is possible, this amendment would need to be inserted.</p><p>
